PRESS DIGEST - New York Times business - May 8 . The New York Times reported the following business stories Thursday : * While Democrats and Republicans discussed the details of the Federal budget plan , Republicans said May 7 , 1997 would be the effective date of any reduction in taxes on capital gains . * The U . S . Federal Communications Commission approved a landmark restructuring of telephone charges which would raise prices for some services and lower them for others . * The government reported that American business productivity grew at a two percent rate in the first quarter . * Viacom reported a first quarter loss but the loss was below analysts forecast because of a strong performance by MTV and the " Private Parts " movie release helped offset weakness at the Blockbuster unit . * Imperial Chemical said it would buy Unilever ' s specialty chemical division for $ 8 billion cash . * News Corp quarterly earnings rose sharply helped by the re - release of the " Star Wars " trilogy and boosted by adding New World Communications Group TV stations . * Transitional Hospitals received a $ 639 million hostile takeover offer from Vencor , after rebuffing a private offer from Vencor and agreeing to a friendly merger pact with privately - held Select Medical . * Four drug makers whose blood products allegedly infected thousands of hemophiliacs with AIDS in the early 1980s will pay about $ 670 million under a settlement approved by a federal judge . * Ad spending by auto makers , traditionally the largest advertising spenders , rose 9 . 4 percent last year . * The Dow Jones fell 139 . 67 points to 7 , 085 . 65 , following previous rallies based on the outlook for earnings , inflation and interest rates . * A U . S . report said the Swiss government failed to honor an agreement which to return hundreds of millions of dollars in assets which Nazis looted from Holocaust victims and European banks . The study also criticized the U . S . government for not pushing the Swiss hard enough at the end of the war to account for the gold . * New York state ' s plan to put all of its three million Medicaid recipients in managed care plans is facing hurdles . * A report , discounted by some analysts , that Japanese , German and U . S . central banks were preparing to sell the dollar caused the currency to decline . * Market place : It is tough to know if Nine West has more problems with accounting or investor relations . * Officials in Texas border towns blame the North American Free Trade Agreement for the relatively depressed economy in these areas . ( ( New York newsdesk 212 - 859 - 1610 ) ) 
